==生平==
===球員===
;早年
Pardew started his career as a part-time player in [[non-League_football|non-League football]] at [[Whyteleafe_F.C.|Whyteleafe]] and [[Epsom_&_Ewell_F.C.|Epsom & Ewell]], whilst working as a [[glazier|glazier]].<ref name="Guardian profile"/> At one stage he gave up football for six months whilst working in the [[Middle_East|Middle East]],<ref name="Guardian profile">{{cite news| title = Rise of the part-timer who almost quit
| accessdate =5 November 2007| url = http://football.guardian.co.uk/News_Story/0,,1769561,00.html| work=The Guardian| location=London| first=Jon| last=Henderson| date=7 May 2006}}</ref> but he returned to football at [[Corinthian_Casuals_F.C.|Corinthian Casuals]] before later having spells at [[Dulwich_Hamlet_F.C.|Dulwich Hamlet]] and [[Yeovil_Town_F.C.|Yeovil Town]]. Pardew was also in the [[England_C_national_football_team|England Semi-Professional]] squad during this time.<ref name="Charlton profile">{{cite web| title = Pardew's Charlton profile| accessdate =16 November 2007
| publisher= Charlton Athletic FC| url = http://www.cafc.co.uk/coachdisplay.ink?skip=4&season=2006/2007}}</ref>

;水晶宮
Pardew moved to [[Football_League_Second_Division|Football League Second Division]] side [[Crystal_Palace_F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in 1987 for a fee of £7,500.<ref name="Charlton profile"/> In 1989, he helped Palace win promotion to the [[Football_League_First_Division|First Division]] after beating [[Blackburn_Rovers_F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] in the [[Football_League_Championship_play-offs#1989|play-offs]]. The following year, in 1990, he scored the winning goal as Palace memorably beat [[Liverpool_F.C.|Liverpool]] 4–3 after extra-time in a thrilling [[FA_Cup|FA Cup]] semi-final at [[Villa_Park_(stadium)|Villa Park]]. He then played in both the final and the final [[Replay_(sports)|replay]] as Palace [[FA_Cup_Final_1990|lost]] to [[Manchester_United_F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref name="Charlton profile"/>

;末年
Pardew moved to [[Charlton_Athletic_F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] in November 1991, and was Charlton's top scorer in the [[1992–93_in_English_football|1992–93]] season with ten goals.<ref name="Charlton profile"/> In 1995, Pardew appeared four times on loan at [[Tottenham_Hotspur_F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] in the [[1995_UEFA_Intertoto_Cup|1995 UEFA Intertoto Cup]]. He played in the team who suffered the embarrassment of being involved in Spurs' record defeat in the history of the club, when they lost 8–0 away to German side [[1._FC_Köln|1. FC Köln]]. Spurs had fielded a team made up of reserves and loanees, including Pardew, for their final group game in Cologne.<ref name="Charlton profile"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/no-picnic-for-english-clubs-by-the-sea-1588438.html|title=No picnic for English clubs by the sea |publisher=[[The_Independent|The Independent]] |date=26 June 1995 |accessdate=7 November 2009| location=London| first=Phil| last=Shaw| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091122205124/http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/no-picnic-for-english-clubs-by-the-sea-1588438.html| archivedate= 22 November 2009 | deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tottenham, Liverpool, Man United and six of the biggest defeats in Europe|url=http://www.talksport.co.uk/magazine/features/2011-04-13/tottenham-liverpool-man-united-and-six-biggest-defeats-europe|publisher=Talksport|accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref>

After rejecting an opportunity to play in [[Hong_Kong|Hong Kong]],<ref name="Charlton profile"/> Pardew then moved to [[Barnet_F.C.|Barnet]], and became a [[player-coach|player-coach]] under manager [[Terry_Bullivant|Terry Bullivant]]. When Bullivant moved to [[Reading_F.C.|Reading]] in 1997, he took Pardew with him as reserve-team manager.<ref name="Guardian profile"/>

;國家隊
At international level Pardew was a member of the [[England_C_national_football_team|England Semi-Professional]] squad during his time in the English non-League playing for Dulwich Hamlet and Yeovil Town.

=== 領隊 ===
;雷丁
Pardew's first experience as manager came in March 1998 when he was appointed as [[Caretaker_manager|caretaker]] after the departure of Bullivant. After the appointment of [[Tommy_Burns_(footballer)|Tommy Burns]] he remained as reserve team manager until the end of the [[1998–99_in_English_football|1998–99]] season, when Reading disbanded their reserve team.<ref>{{cite web| title = Alan Pardew managerial profile| url = http://www.leaguemanagers.com/manager/profile-348.html| publisher = League Managers Association| date = | accessdate =21 September 2007| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070810130238/http://www.leaguemanagers.com/manager/profile-348.html| archivedate= 10 August 2007 | deadurl= no}}</ref> Nevertheless, he was promoted to manager of the club after a successful spell as caretaker in 1999. He turned the club around from relegation fighters to promotion candidates through players, such as [[Jamie_Cureton|Jamie Cureton]], and his régime to increase the fitness of the squad. Pardew also coined his motto "Tenacity, Spirit and Flair" to give his side a psychological edge.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}}

Pardew's Reading side lost 3–2 to [[Walsall_F.C.|Walsall]] in a [[2001_Football_League_Second_Division_play-off_Final|Division Two playoff final]] at the end of the [[2000–01_in_English_football|2000–01]] season, but this was redeemed the next season as the club achieved automatic promotion to Division One. Pardew's first season in the higher division was impressive, as the club finished fourth. They lost in the play-offs once again, this time to [[Wolverhampton_Wanderers_F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]. Pardew was starting to gain a reputation as one of the game's best up and coming young managers.

;韋斯咸
[[File:PardewWHU2006.jpg|thumb]]
Early into the [[2003–04_in_English_football|2003–04]] season, [[West_Ham_United_F.C.|West Ham United]] asked Reading permission to appoint Pardew as their new manager. Although Reading refused permission, Pardew [[resigned|resigned]] from his position forcing the issue. Eventually, a compromise agreement was reached allowing Pardew to become manager at West Ham.<ref name="Pardew free to join West Ham">{{cite news| title = Pardew free to join West Ham
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/3120534.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 18 September 2003| accessdate =26 August 2007}}</ref>

Pardew's first season at West Ham resulted in a [[2004_Football_League_First_Division_play-off_Final|play-off final]] defeat to his former club Crystal Palace.<ref>{{cite news| title = Crystal Palace 1–0 West Ham| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/3750773.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 29 May 2004| accessdate =26 August 2007}}</ref> In the [[2004–05_in_English_football|2004–05 season]] West Ham struggled to find promotion form, with Pardew coming under pressure from the club's supporters.<ref>{{cite news| title = Hammers boss feels the pressure| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/4201197.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 24 January 2005| accessdate =26 August 2007}}</ref> West Ham eventually succeeded in gaining promotion to the [[Premier_League|Premier League]] after defeating [[Preston_North_End_F.C.|Preston North End]] in the [[2005_Football_League_Championship_play-off_Final|play-off final]].<ref>{{cite news| title = West Ham 1–0 Preston| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/4573799.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 30 May 2005| accessdate =26 August 2007| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070829030849/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/4573799.stm| archivedate= 29 August 2007 | deadurl= no}}</ref> Pardew guided the Hammers to ninth place in the Premier League in the [[2005-06_in_English_football|2005–06 season]], which culminated in an appearance in the final of the [[FA_Cup|FA Cup]]. After drawing [[FA_Cup_Final_2006|3–3]] with [[Liverpool_F.C.|Liverpool]] at the end of extra-time, West Ham lost on penalties,<ref>{{cite news| title = Liverpool 3–3 West Ham| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/4756045.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 13 May 2006| accessdate =30 August 2007| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070909064738/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/4756045.stm| archivedate= 9 September 2007 | deadurl= no}}</ref> resulting in the second FA Cup Final defeat of Pardew's career.

In the [[2006–07_in_English_football|2006–07 season]], Pardew was criticised after seeing West Ham through their worst run of defeats in over 70 years which included an exit from the [[UEFA_Europa_League|UEFA Cup]] to [[U.S._Città_di_Palermo|Palermo]] in the very first round<ref>{{cite news| title = Palermo 3–0 West Ham (agg: 4–0)| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/5384280.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 26 September 2006| accessdate =13 December 2010}}</ref> and a [[Football_League_Cup|League Cup]] defeat to [[Chesterfield_F.C.|Chesterfield]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Pardew humiliated after cup exit| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/6082588.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 25 October 2006| accessdate =30 August 2007}}</ref>  West Ham's new owners stated their support for Pardew,<ref>{{cite news| title = Pardew backed by West Ham bidder| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/6041932.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 12 October 2006| accessdate =21 September 2007| first=John| last=Sinnott}}</ref> but on 11 December 2006, following a 4–0 defeat away at [[Bolton_Wanderers_F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] the previous weekend, it was announced that Pardew had been sacked by West Ham. The club statement read: ''"The chairman Mr [[Eggert_Magnússon|Eggert Magnússon]] and the board have been concerned by the performances of recent weeks and feel that it is the right time to make a change in the best interests of the club."''<ref>[http://www.whufc.com/news/?page_id=8586 West Ham United Club Statement], 11 December 2006. Retrieved 30 December 2006.</ref>

;查爾頓
Pardew's absence from management lasted less than two weeks when he was appointed manager of Charlton Athletic on [[Christmas_Eve|Christmas Eve]] 2006, signing a three-and-a-half year contract.<ref>[http://www.sportinglife.com/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/06/12/24/SOCCER_Charlton_Lead.html Reed Leaves Charlton] ''Sporting Life''. Retrieved 21 December 2006; Includes link to interview in RealVideo format</ref> He took over with Charlton in 19th place in the Premier League, with just 12 points and a –20 goal difference, the lowest in the league.  Although Charlton's form improved under Pardew,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/6634445.stm Dean Kiely on Charlton's troubles], BBC Sport. Retrieved 20 June 2007.</ref> he was unable to keep Charlton up, resulting in the first relegation of his career, both as a player and manager.<ref>{{cite news| title = Pardew admits Charlton frailties| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/6633503.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 8 May 2007| accessdate =21 September 2007| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070915184008/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/6633503.stm| archivedate= 15 September 2007 | deadurl= no}}</ref>

Many expected Charlton to bounce back from relegation into the Premier League with signings such as [[Chris_Iwelumo|Chris Iwelumo]] and [[Luke_Varney|Luke Varney]] in the 2007–08 season. But Charlton failed to mount a serious promotion challenge and finished the season in 11th. This put Pardew under pressure going into the 2008–09 season but Charlton started the season off well with victories over Reading and Swansea. However, Charlton's form very quickly deteriorated and they were near the foot of the table after 8 games without a win. After an inept display in a 5–2 home defeat to [[Sheffield_United_F.C.|Sheffield United]] hundreds of supporters remained for more than an hour to condemn their manager, chanting, "We want Pardew out" and "We want our club back" after Charlton had slipped into the Championship's bottom three.<ref>{{cite news| title = Charlton 2–5 Sheff Utd | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/7727279.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 22 November 2008| accessdate =9 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Alan Pardew and Charlton Athletic go their separate ways | url = http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/charlton-athletic/3503383/Alan-Pardew-and-Charlton-Athletic-go-their-separate-ways-Football.html| publisher = www.telegraph.co.uk| date = 22 November 2008| accessdate =9 December 2010| location=London| first=Huw| last=Turbervill}}</ref> On 22 November 2008, Pardew parted company with Charlton by mutual consent.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/7744263.stm Pardew and Charlton part company] BBC Sport</ref>

;修咸頓
Pardew was named the new manager of [[Southampton_F.C.|Southampton]] in the early hours of 17 July 2009,<ref name="Southampton boss">{{cite news| title = Southampton name Pardew as boss| accessdate =16 July 2009| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/southampton/8155056.stm | work=BBC Sport | date=17 July 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090717101742/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/southampton/8155056.stm| archivedate= 17 July 2009 | deadurl= no}}</ref> after the new owner [[Markus_Liebherr|Markus Liebherr]] had taken over the club and sacked [[Mark_Wotte|Mark Wotte]] a day after completing the deal to save The Saints. Pardew's first signing for the club was [[Dan_Harding|Dan Harding]] who signed on a free transfer after being released by [[Ipswich_Town_F.C.|Ipswich Town]]. His first league match in charge was against [[Millwall_F.C.|Millwall]] on 8 August, which ended in a 1–1 draw. He brought many new signings to the club including notable [[League_One|League One]] strikers [[Rickie_Lambert|Rickie Lambert]] and [[Lee_Barnard|Lee Barnard]], the first of whom cost more than £1 million. Pardew led his side up the League One table and despite their 10 point deduction, their challenge for a playoff place was kept alive until there were just two league games remaining.

Pardew led Southampton to the [[2010_Football_League_Trophy_Final|2010 Football League Trophy Final]] at [[Wembley_Stadium|Wembley]], where they won 4–1 against [[Carlisle_United_F.C.|Carlisle United]]. The win gave the club their first trophy since 1976. Five months later Pardew was dismissed by the club,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/southampton/8954162.stm |title=BBC Sport – Football - Southampton sack manager Pardew |publisher=BBC News |date=30 August 2010|accessdate=30 August 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100831012812/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/southampton/8954162.stm| archivedate= 31 August 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Official Club Statement |url=http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10280~2139306,00.html|publisher=Southampton FC|accessdate=31 August 2010|date=30 August 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100831105956/http://www.saintsfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10280~2139306,00.html| archivedate= 31 August 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref> amidst reports of low staff morale and conflicts between Pardew and club chairman, [[Nicola_Cortese|Nicola Cortese]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Jeremy|title=Southampton sack Alan Pardew due to concern over staff morale at St Mary’s|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/southampton/7971476/Southampton-sack-Alan-Pardew-due-to-concern-over-staff-morale-at-St-Marys.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=31 August 2010|location=London|date=31 August 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100902112958/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/southampton/7971476/Southampton-sack-Alan-Pardew-due-to-concern-over-staff-morale-at-St-Marys.html| archivedate= 2 September 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Fletcher|first=Paul|title=Pardew sacking at Saints raises eyebrows|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/paulfletcher/2010/08/pardew_sacking_at_saints_raise.html#248300|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=31 August 2010|date=30 August 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100901174431/http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/paulfletcher/2010/08/pardew_sacking_at_saints_raise.html| archivedate= 1 September 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref>

;紐卡素
On 6 December 2010, [[Chris_Hughton|Chris Hughton]] was sacked as manager of [[Newcastle_United_F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/9261212.stm|title=Boss Chris Hughton sacked by Newcastle United|date=6 December 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=6 December 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101207044123/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/9261212.stm| archivedate= 7 December 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref> Three days later the club confirmed Pardew as the club's new manager on a five and a half year deal. Sky Sports reported that of 40,000 fans taking part in a poll on who should become the next manager, Pardew only received the backing of 5.5% of voters.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_6563242,00.html|title=Pardew lands Newcastle job|last=Parrish|first=Rob|date=9 December 2010|work=SkySports|accessdate=9 December 2010}}</ref>

Pardew stated: "I'm not a [[Geordie|Geordie]] of course, but I'm a football person with a love of the game and I can assure you I bring great drive, desire and commitment to the job. Chris Hughton did a great job last season, guiding the club back to the Premier League, and he continued that good work this season. It is my aim to build on that now and take this club forward."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/newcastle-united/8190898/Alan-Pardew-confirmed-as-Newcastle-manager.html|title=Alan Pardew confirmed as Newcastle manager until 2016|last=Stewart|first=Rob|date=9 December 2010|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=9 December 2010|location=London}}</ref> He acknowledged that he would face a battle to win over players and supporters, and that other managers had texted him to say "you must be mad going there", but he declared: "It's one of the top five clubs in England. It's a daunting prospect but something I couldn't turn down."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/9273388.stm|title=Pardew admits other bosses question his Newcastle move|date=9 December 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=9 December 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101210045723/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/9273388.stm| archivedate= 10 December 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref>

In his first game in charge he led Newcastle to a 3–1 win over [[Liverpool_F.C.|Liverpool]] at [[St_James'_Park|St James' Park]] on 11 December 2010 with goals from [[Kevin_Nolan|Kevin Nolan]], [[Joey_Barton|Joey Barton]] and [[Andy_Carroll|Andy Carroll]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McNulty |first=Phil |title=Newcastle 3–1 Liverpool|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9268294.stm|accessdate=12 December 2010|date=11 December 2010|work=BBC News| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101212044234/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9268294.stm| archivedate= 12 December 2010 | deadurl= no}}</ref> In the club's first home game of 2011, he achieved a notable 5–0 victory over his former club West Ham United.<ref>{{cite news|author=Posted '+ dateCreated +' |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/match_report/0,19764,11065_3284042,00.html |title=Football News | Match Report | Newcastle v West Ham – 5 January 2011 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=5 January 2011 |accessdate=10 January 2011}}</ref> He brought in his own coaching staff in the form of [[John_Carver_(footballer)|John Carver]] as assistant manager,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/jan/18/newcastle-john-carver-alan-pardew |title=Newcastle United | News | Latest News | Latest News | Carver appointed |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=11 January 2011 |location=London| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110119114853/http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/jan/18/newcastle-john-carver-alan-pardew| archivedate= 19 January 2011 | deadurl= no}}</ref> who had worked as assistant to [[Sir_Bobby_Robson|Sir Bobby Robson]] six years earlier. [[Andy_Woodman|Andy Woodman]] was also Pardew's appointment as goalkeeping coach. Soon afterwards Pardew, however, suffered one of the most embarrassing defeats in the club's history as Newcastle went down 3–1 to League 2 side [[Stevenage_F.C.|Stevenage]] in the 3rd round of the [[FA_Cup|FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11678_6642955,00.html |title=Newcastle United | Football | Premier League | Pardew apologises for upset |publisher=Sky Sports |date= 8 January 2011|accessdate=10 January 2011}}</ref>

However, the following month Pardew led the Magpies to one of the most memorable moments in the club's recent history when Newcastle drew 4–4 with [[Arsenal_F.C.|Arsenal]] in an enthralling match at St James' Park on 5 February 2011. Newcastle were 4–0 down by half time only to come back to level the match. This has been seen as one of the most remarkable comebacks in Premier League history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nufc.co.uk/articles/20110206/the-best-comeback-ever-leon_2281670_2286803 |title=Newcastle United | News | Latest News | Latest News | The Best Comeback Ever - Leon |publisher=Nufc.co.uk |date= |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/premier-league/news/detail/item579408/Andrew-Leci:-Goals-Galore!/# |title=Football | Barclays Premier League | Andrew Leci: Goals Galore! |publisher=Espnstar.Com |date= |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref> He secured Newcastle's safety in the Premier League with a 2–1 win over [[Birmingham_City|Birmingham City]] on 7 May 2011, with the club in mid-table. This result was followed by a 2–2 draw at [[Chelsea_F.C.|Chelsea]] and a 3–3 draw against [[West_Bromwich_Albion|West Brom]] at [[St._James'_Park|St. James' Park]]. However, in this match they let a 3–0 goal lead slip meaning they would finish outside the top 10 in 12th place.

In the summer of 2011, Pardew bought many French speaking players such as [[Yohan_Cabaye|Yohan Cabaye]], [[Sylvain_Marveaux|Sylvain Marveaux]] and French-born Senegalese striker, [[Demba_Ba|Demba Ba]].<ref>http://www.nufcblog.com/2011/07/08/coloccini-an-honor-to-be-newcastle-united-captain/ comments</ref> At the start of the 2011–12 season, Pardew led Newcastle to their best start to a Premier League campaign in 17 years, with an unbeaten run of eleven matches in all competitions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Edwards|first=Luke|title=Newcastle United 2 Tottenham Hotspur 2: match report |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/premier-league/8827582/Newcastle-United-2-Tottenham-Hotspur-2-match-report.html|publisher=[[Daily_Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=17 October 2011|date=16 October 2011|location=London}}</ref>

In January 2012, Pardew signed Senegalese striker [[Papiss_Cissé|Papiss Cissé]] from Bundesliga side [[SC_Freiburg|SC Freiburg]]. This was another pivotal signing in the resurgence of Newcastle, as he scored 13 goals in 12 games.

Two days prior to the final match of the season, Pardew won the [[Premier_League_Manager_of_the_Season|Premier League Manager of the Season]] award, becoming the first Newcastle United manager to achieve this. He was given the award after an impressive season with Newcastle where he guided them to a European place for the following season.<ref name="BBC Sport">{{cite web|title=Newcastle United's Alan Pardew named manager of the season|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18042404|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 May 2012|date=11 May 2012}}</ref> He also won the [[League_Managers_Association_Awards#LMA_Manager_of_the_Year|League Managers Association Manager of the Year]] award, which made him the first and only English manager to win the two individual awards in a single Premier League season.<ref name="LMAWINNER">{{cite news |title=Alan Pardew wins LMA award 2012 |url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/news/news-7005.html |work=LMA |publisher=LMA |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref> On 27 September 2012, Pardew signed an eight-year contract extension with the club.<ref>{{cite web|title=Newcastle United manager Alan Pardew has signed a new eight-year contract|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11678/8114243/Newcastle-United-manager-Alan-Pardew-has-been-signed-a-new-eight-year-contract|publisher=Skysports.com}}</ref>

During the 2013 January transfer window Pardew signed a number of players from [[Ligue_1|Ligue 1]] in [[France|France]] including Internationals such as [[Mapou_Yanga-Mbiwa|Mapou Yanga-Mbiwa]], [[Mathieu_Debuchy|Mathieu Debuchy]] and [[Moussa_Sissoko|Moussa Sissoko]] to help boost Newcastle's season. The new signings helped Pardew to guide Newcastle to their first European quarter-final in 8 years as they defeated Russian side [[FC_Anzhi_Makhachkala|Anzhi Makhachkala]] 1-0 on aggregate. On 14 April 2013, Pardew's Newcastle side lost 3-0 to Sunderland at [[St._James'_Park|St. James' Park]], Newcastle's biggest home defeat to Sunderland since [[Bill_McGarry_(footballer)|Bill McGarry]]'s side lost 4–1 in February 1979.

After the retirement of [[Alex_Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]], the subsequent transfer of [[David_Moyes|David Moyes]] to [[Manchester_United_F.C.|Manchester United]], as well as [[Tony_Pulis|Tony Pulis]] leaving [[Stoke_City_F.C.|Stoke City]], Pardew became the second longest-serving manager in the [[Premier_League|Premier League]].<ref>{{cite news|last=COVERDALE|first=DAVID|title=Pards on red alert|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/football/4940715/Alan-Pardew-Second-longest-serving-manager-is-dangerous.html|accessdate=4 June 2013|newspaper=The Sun|date=25 May}}</ref> On 6 December 2013 Pardew was awarded the November [[Premier_League_Manager_of_the_Month|Premier League Manager of the Month]] award after guiding Newcastle to four wins out of four.<ref name="BBC Sport">{{cite web|title=Newcastle's Alan Pardew wins Premier League manager of month|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25259078|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 December 2013|date=6 December 2013}}</ref> He followed this up with the club's first win at [[Old_Trafford|Old Trafford]] in forty-one years, defeating [[Manchester_United_F.C.|Manchester United]] 0–1 on 7 December 2013.<ref name="BBC Sport">{{cite web|title=Manchester United 0–1 Newcastle United|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25164173|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=7 December 2013|date=7 December 2013}}</ref>

