== 爭議 ==
So far in his career, Pardew has been involved in several controversial issues and events. In 2003, the [[BBC|BBC]] described him as being a "dangerous and distant animal" in the media, referring to his public relations abilities, which has led him to making several rash comments.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Pards on the table| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 18 September 2003| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/3099788.stm| first=Stuart| last=Roach}}</ref> When at West Ham, the club employed a media advisor for Pardew to help him win over sceptical fans.<ref name="Guardian profile"/> The following is a list of controversies Pardew has been involved in:
*In September 2003, Pardew resigned from Reading after being refused permission to become manager at West Ham. Reading's chairman [[John_Madejski|John Madejski]] attempted to create an [[injunction|injunction]] in the [[High_Court_of_Justice|High Court]] to prevent him from moving to West Ham. Eventually Reading's legal action was dropped, and Pardew joined West Ham after a period of [[gardening_leave|gardening leave]].<ref name="Pardew free to join West Ham"/>
*In March 2006, Pardew had a dispute with [[Arsenal_F.C.|Arsenal]] manager [[Arsène_Wenger|Arsène Wenger]], after he criticised Arsenal for failing to field an English player in their [[UEFA_Champions_League|UEFA Champions League]] win against [[Real_Madrid_C.F.|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{Cite news| title = Pardew questions Arsenal policy| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 10 March 2006| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4792270.stm}}</ref> Wenger suggested that Pardew was being xenophobic,<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/4793868.stm| title = Dein backs Wenger foreign policy| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 11 March 2006}}</ref> a claim Pardew denied, citing his marriage to a [[Sweden|Swedish]] wife.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Pardew insists he is not a racist| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 13 March 2006| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_ham_utd/4802644.stm}}</ref>
*In November 2006, Pardew had another dispute with Wenger after celebrating West Ham's win over Arsenal.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Wenger & Pardew in touchline row| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 5 November 2006| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6119136.stm}}</ref> Wenger claimed he was provoked into pushing Pardew after Pardew's celebrations at West Ham's late win.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Wenger 'provoked' in Pardew row| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 12 November 2006| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6141516.stm}}</ref> Wenger was later fined by [[the_Football_Association|the Football Association]],<ref>{{Cite news| title = Wenger fined for Pardew incident| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 14 December 2006| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6129384.stm}}</ref> whilst Pardew was cleared of the charges in January 2007.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Pardew cleared of conduct charge| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 4 January 2007| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/charlton_athletic/6232081.stm}}</ref>
*In February 2007, shortly before Pardew's new club Charlton faced West Ham, ''[[The_Sun_(newspaper)|The Sun]]'' published a report documenting a video of one of Pardew's media training sessions he took whilst manager at West Ham. In the video, Pardew jokingly made several disparaging comments about West Ham's fans.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Pardew's 4-letter fan gag| work = The Sun| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 24 February 2007| url = http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/sport/football/article19476.ece| location=London| first=Tom| last=Wells}}</ref>
*In October 2007, Pardew intervened on the pitch in a match against [[Hull_City_A.F.C.|Hull City]] to try to break up a confrontation between Charlton and Hull players after [[Lloyd_Sam|Lloyd Sam]] and [[Ian_Ashbee|Ian Ashbee]] were sent-off. Pardew denied he made the situation worse by intervening.<ref>{{Cite news| title = Hull and Charlton charged by FA| work = BBC Sport| accessdate =16 November 2007| date = 5 October 2007| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/7025939.stm| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20071018052340/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/7025939.stm| archivedate= 18 October 2007 | deadurl= no}}</ref>
*In March 2009, on ''[[Match_of_the_Day_2|Match of the Day 2]]'', Pardew stated that [[Chelsea_F.C.|Chelsea]] midfielder [[Michael_Essien|Michael Essien]] "absolutely [[rape|rape]]s" [[Manchester_City_F.C.|Man City]] player [[Ched_Evans|Ched Evans]] during a midfield tussle for the ball, in the sense that he bested him physically.<ref>{{cite web| title = Alan Pardew Accuses Michael Essien of Rape| work = Ryan Bailey| accessdate =16 March 2009| date = 16 March 2009| url = http://www.thespoiler.co.uk/index.php/2009/03/16/video-alan-pardew-accuses-michael-essien-of-rape| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090320040707/http://www.thespoiler.co.uk/index.php/2009/03/16/video-alan-pardew-accuses-michael-essien-of-rape| archivedate= 20 March 2009 | deadurl= no}}</ref>  The [[BBC|BBC]] said there would be no on-air apology, despite 35 viewer complaints, insisting it had been misheard as "rakes".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7946964.stm BBC pundit sorry for rape comment] BBC News, 16 March 2009</ref>
*On the opening day of the 2012–13 Premier League season against Tottenham Hotspur, Pardew pushed an official after an incident where the ball appeared to go over the touchline, but the referee deemed it to still be in play. Pardew later apologised, citing his behaviour as "ridiculous".
